[1] Sierra Leone: scepticism
Date: Wed 23 Jul 2014
Source: Awoko, Sierra Leone News [edited]
http://awoko.org/2014/07/23/sierra-leone-news-sierra-leoneans-sceptical-about-ebola-reality


Sierra Leoneans sceptical about Ebola reality
---------------------------------------------
As Ebola virus disease [EVD] continues to send people to their grave, many Sierra Leoneans say that the trumpeting of Ebola [virus disease, EVD] by government officials is a way of making money for themselves. This was an argument in a 20 sitter bus that accommodates over 80 passengers in which only one lady was bold to say that Ebola is real.

So many passengers were saying that "the government will declare the country EVD free in September [2014] because that is the time the funding will close." Others were saying in krio [local Creole dialect] 'na lie lie' that is, EVD does not exist at all. Another group of passengers were saying that Ebola does exist in other parts of the world but not yet in Sierra Leone. While others were saying that the government is playing politics, stating that most of the victims are from the East which is the stronghold of the opposition party.

It was based on that argument that Awoko [News] visited Dove Cot and Kissy Road Market to investigate what people think about EVD. Many people were making fun about the issue and were saying that it is not real. A businessman said he did not believe that EVD is real and that the Ministry of Health and Sanitation had never showed the public victims of EVD. "I will never believe that EVD is real, until a victim is disclosed." He says the government is saying that body contact spreads EVD and they have done nothing to address the issue of transportation, where people are squeezed like sardines in public transport. He explains that the public transports usually are very choked up and everybody perspires and breathes on each other.

It was at that juncture that a lady who prefers anonymity said that EVD is real but many people do not believe because the communication strategy used was wrong. She explains that at the beginning of the crisis, government officials were making fun about the issue stating that information was coming from the Ministry of Health, State House, politicians, and civil society, so the public was confused as to who is saying the truth. "It was like in-house fighting, that was why the public is thinking that there is some amount of financial gain," she said. The lady said that EVD is an emergency issue and needs a coordinated approach to address it. She advised that the authorities concerned should go back to the drawing board and see where they have gone wrong in terms of sensitization, so it can be strengthened. "If the public refuses to believe that Ebola is real, then the disease will continue to spread," she said.

Harold Thomas, the health communication officer in the Directorate of Disease Prevention and Control at the Ministry of Health, said EVD is real and as of 21 Jul 2014, 139 have been confirmed dead. He said they have done a lot in terms of sensitizing Sierra Leoneans, stating that most of them have heard the information but are refusing to accept it because of their social and cultural background. Thomas said the sensitization had started long before EVD entered the country, and it is still in progress. He said they have engaged leaders of different groups and are also doing face-to-face sensitization. He encouraged Sierra Leoneans to join the fight against EVD, stating that EVD is real.

[byline: Emmanuella Kallon]

