[3] Liberia: hospitals avoided, closed
Date: Wed 23 Jul 2014
Source: AllAfrica, The New Dawn (Monrovia) report [edited]
http://allafrica.com/stories/201407231033.html


The Christian run United Methodist Hospital in Ganta has recorded what is said to be its 1st EVD death, months after it reported the 1st patient it diagnosed during the initial outbreak of the virus there. Hospital officials told the New Dawn correspondent in the county that a 36 year old man from Monrovia and had been transferred to the hospital. Both the hospital's chief medical doctor and chief administrator, Dr Albert Willicor and Mr Victor Doolakeh told our correspondent that the victim had spent a week at the hospital before his demise. The victim was the 2nd Ebola patient to have reported at the hospital. It can be recalled that the 1st suspected Ebola patient diagnosed at the hospital was from neighboring Guinea, where the virus 1st broke out before spreading to Liberia and Sierra Leone. His transfer to the JFK Medical Hospital in Monrovia at the time sparked a controversy, with condemnation for the doctor who ordered the transfer.

Our correspondent says the reported EVD death at the hospital has sent fear among residents of the city and its surrounding communities. The Ganta United Methodist Hospital, is one of the hospitals that receives patients from Guinea, Ivory Coast [Cote d'Ivoire] and other nearby counties here, but the news of an EVD patient death there is turning [other] patients away. Our correspondent who visited the hospital said some health workers were seen well dressed in their EVD [personal protective equipment], while others were working [without it?].

The correspondent also said that the reported EVD death in Ganta has forced citizens to revert to buying drugs over the counter and from street drugs peddlers. This news comes days after health authorities at the GW Harley hospital shut-down the only government hospital following news of 2 EVD patients there. Health authorities there have refused to comment on the matter.

[byline: Fohn Doloquee]

