[In Sierra Leone, 7 weeks after EVD was 1st confirmed in the country, there is still a lot of denial of the disease, for complex reasons.

In Liberia, there seems to be a problem with the system for rapidly responding to reports of EVD cases, and a misunderstanding -- not only by the public -- of how the disease spread. It is not airborne; as long as there is no unprotected contact with a sick or dead victim or surfaces that they have touched, there is no danger of being infected. Spraying with 1:100 bleach solution any surfaces that might have been contaminated by an EVD case is effective against ebolavirus, but fumigation with insecticide (if that is what is meant) has no effect on viruses spread by contact, like ebolavirus.

In Liberia, on the one hand the government has reportedly released USD 500 000 to combat EVD, but on the other, the country's Senate blocked a resolution from the lower house to use USD 1.5 million earmarked for the 26 Jul 2014 Independence Day celebrations for fighting EVD instead, saying it was unconstitutional to reallocate those particular funds http://allafrica.com/stories/201407230941.html.
This leaves the bulk of financing Liberia's struggle against EVD to outside agencies.

The sooner point-of-care tests for ebolavirus can be deployed in the 3 countries, the sooner testing can be done at all hospitals there instead of only in those few with specially-equipped labs using expensive reagents and equipment and expatriate experts.

Rwanda, which borders Ituri district, Orientale Province, DR Congo, where a suspected EVD outbreak is currently occurring (see ProMED archive 20140721.2624831) has 32 trained people on the alert for imported EVD cases (http://allafrica.com/stories/201407230513.html?page=2) and information about EVD posted on its Rwanda Biomedical Center website http://www.rbc.gov.rw/spip.php?article696.
Those are prudent moves. West African countries that have not yet seen an EVD case, take note. - Mod.JW]
